###### INTERPRETATION #1 of Pre-QC: These plots showing the pre-QC quality scores of the raw sequencing data for the project, which aggregate 29 sequencing files, and were generated with 2x300 bp sequencing on an Illumina MiSeq Sequencer: 1. Early Bases Have a Drop in Quality (~Cycle 0-10) Both forward and reverse reads show a slight drop in quality at the beginning (~Cycle 0-10). However, this drop remains mostly above Q30, which is acceptable. Therefore, I dont need to use the trimLeft parameter to remove the first several bases in both forward and reverse reads. 2. High Quality in Mid-Read (~Cycle 10-250) The sequencing quality is stable and above Q30 across most of the sequencing cycle/read (Cycle 10-300). This suggests that most of the read length is high-quality and can be retained. 3. Decline in Reverse Reads After ~200 Cycles The reverse reads exhibit a notable drop in quality after ~210 cycles, dropping below Q30. The decline is more severe in reverse reads than in forward reads, indicating a high sequencing error rate. This suggests that truncating the reverse reads around Cycle 200-220 might improve quality. Therefore, I will truncate the read using truncLen = 210 to remove those final 90 poor-quality bases at the end of the read. The beginning of the read is ~30 so we are ok at the beginning of the read. 4. Forward Reads Maintain Quality Slightly Longer (~Cycle 230-300) The forward reads show a more gradual decline in quality after Cycle 230, but they remain above Q30 longer than the reverse reads. The final cycles (~280-300) show a steep drop in quality, which is common for Illumina sequencing. This suggests that truncating forward reads around Cycle ~280 to remove poor-quality bases. Therefore, I will truncate the read using trunclen = 280 to remove those final 20 poor-quality bases at the end of the read.

Filter and Trim Reads

# Assign and write out filtered fastq files 
# Therefore, we do not need to trim the primers, because they were not sequenced
filtered_reads <- 
  filterAndTrim(fwd = forward_reads, filt = filtered_forward_reads,
              rev = reverse_reads, filt.rev = filtered_reverse_reads,
              maxN = 0,
              # The sequence quality was not bad, so I choose to use maxEE = c(2,2) to make it better
              maxEE = c(2,2), 
              # Don't need to remove the first several bases at the beginning of both forward and reverse reads
              trimLeft = c(0, 0),
              # Trim final 20 bases in the forward & trim final 90 bases in the reverse
              truncLen = c(280, 210), 
              truncQ = 2, rm.phix = TRUE, compress = TRUE, multithread = TRUE)

###### INTERPRETATION #2 of Post-QC: The plots above show the post-QC quality scores of the sequencing data after applying quality filtering and trimming. Quality filtering successfully removed poor-quality reads and trimmed low-quality tails, leading to improved overall read quality. 1. Forward Reads Post-QC The forward reads maintain high quality (Q30+) throughout most of the read length. A slight decline in quality is visible after ~230 cycles, but still largely above a Phred of 30. 2. Reverse Reads Post-QC Initial bases (~0-10 cycles) remain stable, suggesting that any low-quality bases were effectively trimmed. The mid-read section (~10-170 cycles) maintains strong Q30+ quality with minimal degradation. A quality drop-off is still visible after ~170 cycles, but it is much less severe than before, meaning the QC process effectively removed the worst low-quality regions while preserving usable data.

Read Retention Post-QC

# Make output into dataframe 
filtered_df <- as.data.frame(filtered_reads) %>%
  mutate(percent.retained = reads.out/reads.in)

# Intuition check
# Visualize it in table format 
DT::datatable(filtered_df)
# Let's calculate some statistics
read_stats_df <- 
  filtered_df %>%
  reframe(median_reads_in = median(reads.in),
          median_reads_out = median(reads.out),
          median_percent_retained = (median(reads.out)/median(reads.in)),
          max_percent_retained = max(reads.out/reads.in),
          min_percent_retained = min(reads.out/reads.in))

# Take a look at it!
read_stats_df
##   median_reads_in median_reads_out median_percent_retained max_percent_retained
## 1           45573            41577               0.9123165            0.9229034
##   min_percent_retained
## 1            0.7696574
# Plot it 
numSeqs_QC_dotplot <-
  filtered_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reads.in, y = reads.out)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5, size = 2) + 
  labs(x = "# of Raw Seqs", 
       y = "# of Seqs Retained") + 
  # Now let's add a 1:1 line for reference of keeping 100% of the reads
  geom_abline(slope=1, intercept = 0, color = "deeppink")

# Now, let's look at the number of reads retained in a histogram
numRetained_QC_histplot <- 
  filtered_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reads.out)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  labs(x = "# of Seqs Retained", 
       y = "# of Samples") 

# Create a histogram of percent reads retained in a histogram
percSeqs_QC_histplot <- 
  filtered_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = percent.retained)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  labs(x = "% of Seqs Retained", 
       y = "# of Samples") + 
  # Set the scale to be between 0-1 (0-100%)
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1))

# Now, let's put the plots together
numSeqs_QC_dotplot + numRetained_QC_histplot + percSeqs_QC_histplot + 
  plot_annotation(tag_levels = 'A')

###### INTERPRETATION #3 of Post-QC Statistics: This figure presents three panels showing how many sequences were retained after quality filtering and trimming in the DADA2 pipeline.

Panel A: Scatter Plot of Raw vs.Retained Sequences X-axis: Number of raw sequences before filtering. Y-axis: Number of sequences retained after filtering. Pink Line: The diagonal line represents perfect retention (i.e., no sequences lost). Interpretation of Panel A: Most points are close to the diagonal, suggesting good read retention across samples. Some points fall below the diagonal, indicating that a few samples lost a moderate number of reads. No extreme outliers, meaning no sample was unexpectedly depleted. Overall: The filtering step was effective while preserving most sequences, ensuring sufficient data retention.

Panel B: Histogram of the Number of Sequences Retained per Sample X-axis: Number of sequences retained per sample. Y-axis: Number of samples with that many retained sequences. Interpretation of Panel B: Most samples retained between ~10,000 and 20,000 or between ~35,000 and 55,000 sequences, indicating that the majority of data was preserved. A small number of samples have lower retention, but there is no drastic loss. Overall: The filtering process successfully retained a consistent number of reads across most samples.

Panel C: Histogram of Percent of Sequences Retained X-axis: Proportion (%) of sequences retained per sample. Y-axis: Number of samples at each proportion. Interpretation of Panel C. The majority of samples retained 7595% of their reads, indicating successful quality filtering. Median retention is ~93% (good); Max retention: ~95% (great); Min retention: 75% (good).

Quality Score Improvements 1. Forward Reads (Pre vs.Post-QC) Beginning of read: No base was trimmed at the beginning of both forward and reverse reads, which makes sense due to good initial quality (~Q35). Middle of read: The quality remains consistently high Q30-Q40 across most cycles/bases. End of read: While a slight drop in the last ~20 cycles/bases remain, the trimming step remove the lowest-quality bases. 2. Reverse Reads (Pre vs.Post-QC) Beginning of read: No base was trimmed at the beginning of both forward and reverse reads, which makes sense due to good initial quality (~Q35). Middle of read: Mid-read quality (~10-180bp) remains strong. End of read: The trailing end of the reverse reads still shows some degradation, but its significantly improved from pre-QC. The lowest-quality bases have been trimmed, but reverse reads still have some expected drop-off after ~180 cycles (this is typical for Illumina sequencing).
